Motivation: provide a public API that can be consumed by modules like [suspend-express](https://github.com/jmar777/suspend-express), [co-express](https://github.com/mciparelli/co-express), etc.

With the growing popularity of generators-as-coroutines, it has become desirable to write middleware using generator functions.  E.g.,

``` javascript
app.get('/foo/:id', function*(req, res, next) {
    res.json(yield FooModel.find({ id: req.params.id }));
});
```

Currently this requires mucking around with [undocumented APIs](https://github.com/jmar777/suspend-express/blob/v0.1.0/lib/suspend-express.js#L12) and [monkey patching](https://github.com/jmar777/suspend-express/blob/v0.1.0/lib/suspend-express.js#L33).

However, if express were to expose, say, an `express.registerHandlerTransform(mapFn)` (I'm sure that name can be improved on), the implementation of these modules could become much more sensible.  E.g.,

``` javascript
express.registerHandlerTransform(function(handler) {
    return wrapHandlerInSomeGeneratorRunner(handler);
});
```

As convenient as that is, the main advantage isn't really the implementation simplicity, but rather the fact that it's based around a supported API and less likely to break when express is updated.  The performance implications should be negligible, as this is a setup-phase only operation, rather than per-request.

Additionally, while I obviously have my own use case in mind here, I would anticipate this API would have several uses outside of the examples provided above, including application-specific transformation logic.

Thoughts?  I'd be happy to get my hands dirty if an API could be agreed on.

